Visualizing distributions, means, and time trends in the theatre dataset¶

Russell Romney¶

UI DScompViz¶

In this brief visualization exercise I will visualize summary characteristics in the theatre dataset in order to get a feel for the theatre industry.

First, I want to find out the trend in the overall number of shows over time by year:

We can see that the number of shows grew dramatically through the first half of the 1990s. However, we can surmise from our knowledge of the theatre industry's lasting reputation this fact merely represents a problem of data collection: the data may not have been fully representative of the industry during those years. We can also see that the number of performances has stayed relatively steady for the last three decades, with a slight dropoff in the last year of data collection.

Next, I want to look at monthly factors: does the number of shows per day vary throughout the month, or is it equal? My initial guess is that the day of the month will not show discernable differences but that the month itself will.

The distribution of shows throughout the month shows that, as I guessed initially, the day of the month does not have an impact on the number of shows.

What about the distribution of shows by month? My guess is that the number of shows varies significantly by month, seeing as tourism/free time is cyclical annually, and I'm guessing that many showgoers are tourist or at least far-away visitors.

My guess is correct: the distribution of shows changes throughout the year: show volume has two peaks in the late spring/early summer period and in the holiday season of November/December. This makes intuitive sense as shows are more accessible as school gets out initially and the weather improves, while the holiday season is big for big events and themed performances.

I move on to attendance characteristics of the theatres themselves. First, what is the distribution of filled capacity? That is, how often are theatres full and how often is there a lot of extra space?

It seems that most of the time, theatres are mostly full. However, there is a long, fat tail to this distribution in which theatres are only 40%-80% filled; there seems to be a significant amount of slack in theatre attendance.

Next I turn to distribution of nominal attendance figures: what's the most common weekly attendance number for theatres?

Weekly attendance seems to hover around 7,500 in a semi-normal distribution. This makes good sense to me, as a theatre could give five performances per week with 1,500 attendees at each, to reach that mark. From personal experience, I can say that a theatre with more than this number of people becomes uncomfortably large.

But how many performances are there, really, per week at an average theater? If there are not as many as I assume, perhaps the sense I find the previous plot to make may not exist after all. Specifically, I am interested in the relationship between how many times per week the theatre offers a performance and how much the theatre makes per week. Intuitively, I can guess that the distribution will be bimodal at the extremes: theatres hosting only one performance per week will build hype for that performance and have high prices due to performance scarcity, while theatres that have a lot of shows will also make a lot of money because of how many shows they offer.

I find that my analysis was partially correct: theatres with but a single performance per week earn far more than theatres with more than one. I was incorrect, however, in my prediction that revenue increases with number of performances; weekly revenue doesn't change a lot from 2-16 performances per week.

With regards to attendance vs capacity, I am interested to know the strength of the relationship between nominal attendance and percent capacity filled. Intuitively, this relationship should be obvious and linear, but I'll inspect it nonetheless.

Indeed, I do find a nearly linear relationship between nominal attendance and filled capacity, but we find an interesting phenomenon: it looks like either a) larger theatres or b) more shows per week could explain why higher weekly attendance leads to far higher capacity than would be linearly expected.

I'll check that here: do bigger theatres tend to fill up more?

So we find that there is no significant relationship between the size of the venue and how often it is filled.

My final exploration will look at time trends. I want to look at how theatres' attendance figures have changed over time. To do this I will map weekly attendance figures for each individual theater for each of the ~1300 weeks in the dataset. Each theatre's plot will show attendance trends, periods of no performances, and cyclical factors.

I find it fascinating to note the number of theatres that have closed down; it seems that this would be a afar more stable market.

Thanks for following along in this visualization! I don't have any other specific commentary on this portion, but scroll to your heart's content and enjoy the trends and/or notable insights you may find for each theatre!

(note: It is unfortunate that this use of Seaborn's factorplot function does not result in a compact output.)
